result.execSummary:
The defendant Bradley J. Obarski was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Fail/Report to Jail (Misdemeanor) [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.425(1r)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.

With Huber and Good Time Credit.
Consecutive to: to any other sentence.
DNA sample to be provided and surcharge assessed.

11:45 am case called. Defendant Bradley J. Obarski in court with attorney John B. Selsing.  Defendant Bradley J. Obarski in custody.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Agreement stated on record. Attorney Selsing concurs.   Defendant advised of permissible punishment.  Plea QN reviewed w/Defendant.  Plea colloquy entertained.  Collateral consequences explained. Chapter 950 compliance addressed.  Plea: No Contest.   Court accepts plea and enters JOC. Statement by DA Blader. Statement by Attorney Selsing. Statement by defendant. Court sentences defendant to: 13 days WCJ with Huber and Good Time Credit. Credit for 8 days served. Consecutive to any other sentence. Costs to be paid within 60 days or payment plan.  DNA Sample and Surcharge ordered by the Court.  Defendant advised of right to expunge DNA record through the Department of Justice. Appeal Rights Given.
